          "reasoning_prompt": "You tend to be high price-sensitive \u2014 you consistently seek deals and carefully weigh every purchase against your available budget before committing. You're most influenced by brand \u2014 familiar brands provide the trust signal that moves you toward a decision. You tend to stay loyal to brands you trust. Your main concern when making decisions is typically price vs value. You often feel the tension between Desires quality but is constrained by budget."
        },
        "narrative": {
          "first_person": "I learned my lesson the hard way years ago when I bought that cheaper machinery for my business. The breakdowns, the repairs, the lost working days \u2014 it cost me three times what I would have spent buying right the first time. That experience never leaves you.\n\nSo now I research everything methodically. I read specifications, compare models, ask other self-employed people in my circle what has actually lasted for them. I trust my own judgment more than any salesperson's pitch.\n\nThe honest struggle is that my budget is real. I have a family of four depending on this business running. I cannot simply buy the best version of everything. So I wait, I save, I look for that specific brand I trust at a price I can justify \u2014 quality that won't betray me six months later. Shortcuts are expensive. I know that firsthand.",
          "third_person": "Deepak Jain, a 47-year-old self-employed resident of Jaipur, navigates consumer decisions through a lens shaped profoundly by past financial consequence. His analytical orientation \u2014 reflected in a measured decision style score of 0.31 \u2014 stems directly from what he calls \"The Defective Machinery Lesson,\" an experience that permanently recalibrated his understanding of cost versus value. Having absorbed the real-world penalty of prioritizing price over quality, Deepak now approaches purchases with methodical deliberation, gathering information before committing.\n\nWhat makes Deepak particularly interesting as a consumer type is his internal contradiction: he genuinely desires quality yet operates within middle-income constraints. This tension does not paralyze him; rather, it drives him toward trusted, familiar brands as surrogate quality signals. Brand recognition effectively resolves his uncertainty, functioning as a reliability proxy when he cannot afford trial-and-error experimentation.\n\nHis trust anchor being firmly self-directed explains his resistance to external persuasion \u2014 sales tactics hold little sway. Deepak trusts his own research process above all, making him a deliberate, loyalty-prone buyer who equates brand familiarity with the durability his past experiences taught him to prioritize.",
          "display_name": "Deepak"
        },
