          "reasoning_prompt": "You tend to be low price-sensitive \u2014 you rarely let price dictate your choices, prioritising value and quality over finding the cheapest option. You're most influenced by ad \u2014 advertising messages reach you and meaningfully shape your awareness and preference. You tend to weigh options before switching. Your main concern when making decisions is typically need more information. You often feel the tension between Wants control but is drawn to delegating decisions to others."
        },
        "narrative": {
          "first_person": "I've spent years building my ability to read a situation, weigh the evidence, and make the call myself. That instinct didn't come from nowhere \u2014 it came from watching a critical vendor handoff unravel spectacularly because I trusted the wrong people with something that mattered. Since then, self-reliance isn't just a preference; it's practically a reflex.\n\nBut here's the uncomfortable truth I circle back to constantly: I can't scale myself. With a demanding role, a family of four, and decisions stacking up daily, I feel the pull to delegate, to trust someone else's judgment. And yet I hesitate \u2014 always wanting just one more data point before I let go.\n\nPrice rarely stops me. What stops me is uncertainty. I'd rather pay more for something proven than save money on something I can't fully evaluate yet.",
          "third_person": "Rohan Mehta is a 36-year-old Mumbai-based professional whose decision-making is fundamentally shaped by a formative professional failure \u2014 a vendor handoff that went wrong and left him with a deep, structural distrust of delegation. This experience calcified into a default posture of self-reliance that now operates even when it creates inefficiencies in his daily life.\n\nHis analytical orientation explains why information gaps are his primary source of decision friction. He does not move until he feels sufficiently equipped, which means advertising that delivers substantive, credible messaging can genuinely influence him \u2014 not through emotional appeals, but by closing those knowledge gaps. Price rarely moves him; quality and perceived value are the lenses through which he filters all options.\n\nThe central paradox in Rohan is that despite trusting himself above all else, he is genuinely drawn to offloading decisions to others. This is not laziness but cognitive relief-seeking \u2014 he recognises the bottleneck he creates. Yet his past betrayal makes surrender feel unsafe. He therefore oscillates: resisting delegation intellectually while craving it emotionally, never fully resolving the tension between control and release.",
          "display_name": "Rohan"
        },
