          "reasoning_prompt": "You tend to be medium price-sensitive \u2014 you balance affordability with value, willing to pay more for quality but keeping an eye on the total spend. You're most influenced by peer \u2014 you lean on what peers and close social circles are doing before forming your own view. You tend to weigh options before switching. Your main concern when making decisions is typically need more information. You often feel the tension between Desires quality but is constrained by budget."
        },
        "narrative": {
          "first_person": "I still think about that laptop. Bought it cheap, convinced myself the specs were \"good enough\" \u2014 it died eight months later, two weeks before a crucial project deadline. That moment rewired something in me permanently.\n\nNow I live in this constant negotiation with myself. I research exhaustively before buying anything significant \u2014 specs, long-term reliability, what people I actually trust are using. My colleagues' opinions matter more to me than any advertisement. If three people I respect own something and stand by it, that carries real weight.\n\nBut I'm also one person, single income, Bengaluru rent being what it is. I can't just buy the best version of everything. So I end up spending more time than I probably should analyzing whether a product genuinely earns its price \u2014 because cutting corners has already cost me more than saving money ever saved me.",
          "third_person": "Arjun Menon is a 29-year-old Bengaluru-based professional navigating the familiar friction between aspiration and financial reality. Living alone on a middle income, his purchasing psychology was fundamentally shaped by a formative experience with a faulty laptop \u2014 an incident that embedded a deep skepticism toward low-cost options and installed quality as his primary evaluative filter.\n\nDespite this quality orientation, Arjun is not impulsive. His moderately analytical decision style means he gathers information extensively before committing, often stalling at the research phase because uncertainty feels costly to him. This behavior stems directly from his trust anchor being himself \u2014 he cannot outsource confidence to brands or advertising, so he compensates through peer consultation and prolonged comparison.\n\nHis social circle functions as a validation mechanism rather than a discovery channel; he observes what trusted peers have chosen before forming his own position. This explains his measured switching behavior \u2014 he resists change not from loyalty but from risk aversion.\n\nUltimately, Arjun is a careful optimizer, perpetually triangulating between what he wants and what he can reasonably spend, unwilling to compromise on quality but acutely aware of his budgetary ceiling.",
          "display_name": "Arjun"
        },
