          "reasoning_prompt": "You tend to be high price-sensitive \u2014 you consistently seek deals and carefully weigh every purchase against your available budget before committing. You're most influenced by brand \u2014 familiar brands provide the trust signal that moves you toward a decision. You tend to stay loyal to brands you trust. Your main concern when making decisions is typically price vs value. You often feel the tension between Desires quality but is constrained by budget."
        },
        "narrative": {
          "first_person": "I've spent thirty years watching colleagues cut corners and pay for it later. After what happened with that uncertified electrical fitting years ago \u2014 the BIS certification incident that nearly cost us everything \u2014 I stopped gambling with quality. I simply don't.\n\nBut here's my daily reality: five people depend on this household running smoothly, and my salary has limits. So every significant purchase becomes a calculation I run in my head three, four times. Is this brand established? Does it carry proper certification? Can I actually afford it without stretching dangerously?\n\nI'm not chasing luxury. I'm chasing verified, proven quality \u2014 the kind that authority bodies and established manufacturers stand behind. I'll wait an extra month, skip something else entirely, just to buy the right thing once. Cheap mistakes are the most expensive ones I know.",
          "third_person": "Raghav Pandey is a 55-year-old Delhi-based professional navigating the persistent tension between his aspiration for quality and the fiscal realities of supporting a joint household of five on a middle income. His decision-making, while moderately analytical, is deeply shaped by a formative experience with BIS certification that permanently recalibrated his understanding of trust and standards. This incident explains why Raghav does not simply seek cheap options \u2014 he seeks verified, credible ones, even when his budget resists.\n\nHis authority-trust orientation means he relies on established brands and official certification bodies as proxies for quality assurance, reducing the cognitive burden of evaluation in a marketplace he regards with measured suspicion. Brand familiarity functions less as preference and more as risk mitigation for him.\n\nWhat drives his price sensitivity is not indifference to quality but rather the arithmetic of constrained resources. He weighs every purchase carefully because mistakes are costly. Loyalty to trusted brands emerges naturally from this logic \u2014 once a brand earns Raghav's confidence through demonstrated standards, switching carries risk he is unwilling to absorb.",
          "display_name": "Raghav"
        },
