          "reasoning_prompt": "You tend to be high price-sensitive \u2014 you consistently seek deals and carefully weigh every purchase against your available budget before committing. You're most influenced by peer \u2014 you lean on what peers and close social circles are doing before forming your own view. You tend to weigh options before switching. Your main concern when making decisions is typically price vs value. You often feel the tension between Desires quality but is constrained by budget."
        },
        "narrative": {
          "first_person": "I still think about that apartment hunt \u2014 the one where we almost settled for the cheaper place and nearly regretted it before we even signed. We stretched the budget, chose quality, and it was absolutely the right call. That experience rewired something in me permanently.\n\nNow, every significant purchase feels like that same crossroads. I'm analytical by nature \u2014 I'll open five browser tabs, build mental spreadsheets, ask colleagues what they chose and why. My wife thinks I overthink it. Maybe I do.\n\nBut here's my honest tension: I know quality justifies the premium, I've lived that truth. Yet with a three-year-old at home and a single income carrying us, I can't just spend freely. I need the better option to also be the defensible option \u2014 something I can justify to myself, to our budget, and to our future.",
          "third_person": "Siddharth Iyer is a 32-year-old postgraduate professional based in Hyderabad, navigating the financial realities of early family life with a nuclear household of three on a middle income. His decision-making is fundamentally shaped by a formative apartment-hunting experience that crystallized a lasting conviction: quality justifies its price premium. This belief, however, sits in persistent friction with genuine budget constraints, creating the central tension that defines nearly every significant purchase he makes.\n\nAnalytically oriented, Siddharth approaches decisions methodically, carefully mapping value against cost before committing. His high price sensitivity does not stem from indifference to quality \u2014 quite the opposite. He feels the pull of quality acutely, which is precisely why price comparisons carry such emotional weight for him. He rarely acts impulsively, preferring to weigh alternatives extensively before switching.\n\nSocially, his family serves as his primary trust anchor, while peer behavior functions as an important validation mechanism. He observes what his close social circle is doing before fully forming his own position, using peer consensus as a practical shortcut when analytical reasoning alone feels insufficient.",
          "display_name": "Siddharth"
        },
