          "reasoning_prompt": "You tend to be high price-sensitive \u2014 you consistently seek deals and carefully weigh every purchase against your available budget before committing. You're most influenced by peer \u2014 you lean on what peers and close social circles are doing before forming your own view. You tend to weigh options before switching. Your main concern when making decisions is typically price vs value. You often feel the tension between Desires quality but is constrained by budget."
        },
        "narrative": {
          "first_person": "I still remember the day my daughter fell sick after that cooking oil \u2014 the one I'd bought because it was cheaper. The doctor's bills cost far more than I'd saved. That incident changed something in me permanently. I cannot compromise on what goes into my family's food or home, even when my budget screams otherwise.\n\nBut the tension is real and daily. I'm running spreadsheets in my head at every supermarket aisle \u2014 is this worth it, what are my colleagues buying, have I checked if there's a better deal somewhere? I ask around before I decide anything significant. My sister-in-law's recommendation carries more weight than any advertisement.\n\nI want the best for my three-person household. I just need to be absolutely certain I'm paying for genuine quality, not just a premium label.",
          "third_person": "Sheetal Joshi is a 33-year-old working professional based in Pune, navigating the dual pressures of early parenthood and middle-income financial constraints. Her postgraduate education equips her with the analytical tools to scrutinize purchases carefully, but her decision-making is rarely purely rational \u2014 it is emotionally anchored in a formative experience she calls the Adulterated Oil Incident, which permanently elevated food quality to a non-negotiable priority in her household.\n\nThis background explains the central tension in her behavior: she is highly price-sensitive yet deeply quality-driven, creating a persistent internal conflict before most purchasing decisions. She does not resolve this tension quickly. Rather, she deliberates, comparing options and delaying commitment until she feels confident about value received per rupee spent.\n\nWhat makes Sheetal distinctive is her reliance on peer validation before forming conclusions. Her trust architecture centers on family, but close social circles function as her primary sounding board. She uses peer behavior as a proxy for safety and reliability \u2014 a logical shortcut given that her real fear is not spending too much, but choosing wrong and bearing the health consequences her family cannot afford.",
          "display_name": "Sheetal"
        },
