  "sarvam_enrichment": [
    {
      "enrichment_applied": true,
      "enrichment_provider": "sarvam",
      "enrichment_scope": "narrative_and_examples",
      "persona_id": "pg-pg-002",
      "enriched_narrative": {
        "first_person": "I research everything before I buy \u2014 spreadsheets, ingredient lists, JustDial and 1mg review threads. But honestly? The moment a friend I trust says \"I've been using this for six months, it's been great,\" something in me relaxes in a way no amount of data can replicate. After what happened with that formula scare and the FSSAI notice, I stopped believing what brands say about themselves entirely. Marketing means nothing to me now. What matters is whether someone I know, someone whose judgment I respect, has actually lived with a product and vouched for it. Price doesn't move me \u2014 if anything, suspiciously cheap makes me walk away faster. I want to control every decision that comes into my home, especially with my daughter here. But I've learned that control sometimes means knowing whose instincts to borrow.",
        "third_person": "Priya Sharma is a 34-year-old Mumbai-based researcher and working mother whose decision-making is shaped less by convenience or cost and more by an internalized standard of quality that became non-negotiable after a formative contaminated formula scare early in her motherhood, when she cross-referenced FSSAI notices and pediatrician opinions across WhatsApp mother groups. That experience fundamentally restructured her trust architecture, stripping away confidence in brand marketing and redirecting it toward peer validation \u2014 particularly through her active mother networks and professional circles \u2014 as her primary source of reliable information.\n\nHer analytical disposition means she rarely acts without first accumulating sufficient evidence through platforms like 1mg and JustDial, yet she consistently outsources the initial filtering of that evidence to her close social network. This reveals the central tension in her behavior: she craves control over outcomes but is psychologically drawn to delegating the discovery process to trusted peers, effectively using their experiences as a proxy for her own research.\n\nHer low price sensitivity is not indifference to value but rather a recalibrated definition of it \u2014 quality is value, and anything less represents unacceptable risk. Once she identifies a brand that meets her threshold, loyalty follows naturally, since switching carries informational costs she is unwilling to absorb without peer reassurance."
      },
      "cultural_references_added": [
        "FSSAI (Food Safety and Standards Authority of India) \u2014 regulatory body reference traceable to formula scare life story",
