    {
      "enrichment_applied": true,
      "enrichment_provider": "sarvam",
      "enrichment_scope": "narrative_and_examples",
      "persona_id": "pg-pg-013",
      "enriched_narrative": {
        "first_person": "I still think about that ThinkPad I bought before my first internship. I'd read every spec sheet twice, cross-checked three Reddit threads and TechEncircle posts, and called a friend who actually owned the model. Spent two weeks on it. But when I finally stretched my budget by four thousand rupees for the better build quality, it held up through two years of late-night projects without a single complaint. That decision taught me something I carry into every major purchase now.\n\nLiving alone in Bengaluru on a mid-level salary means I can't afford mistakes. So I don't rush. I dig into reviews on sites like 91mobiles and Amazon, filter out the obvious shills, and wait for patterns in what real users consistently say. Quality matters deeply to me \u2014 but I need to justify every premium rupee with actual evidence, not marketing copy. The tension never really goes away.",
        "third_person": "Nikhil Bhat is a 25-year-old postgraduate working full-time in a Bengaluru analytics firm on a middle income while living alone in a one-person household. His decision-making is rooted in a quiet but persistent tension: he genuinely values quality, yet his budget imposes real limits that he cannot ignore.\n\nWhat makes Nikhil analytically distinctive is that he does not simply trust peer opinion at face value. His formative laptop decision \u2014 researching on Reddit, TechEncircle, and 91mobiles forums before stretching for a ThinkPad \u2014 taught him that community consensus is a useful signal, but only after personal verification. This explains why online reviews and tech communities are central to his research process: he absorbs them critically rather than deferring automatically.\n\nHis medium price sensitivity reflects calculated willingness to stretch spending when quality justifiably warrants it, not impulsiveness. He delays switching until informationally satisfied, which is why his dominant concern is consistently needing more data before acting. Nikhil essentially operates as his own auditor\u2014gathering peer data through platforms he trusts, stress-testing it against his own reasoning, and only then permitting himself to spend beyond comfort if the case holds firm."
      },
      "cultural_references_added": [
        "ThinkPad (specific device brand, not generic 'laptop')",
        "four thousand rupees (currency-specific anchor)",
