    {
      "enrichment_applied": true,
      "enrichment_provider": "sarvam",
      "enrichment_scope": "narrative_and_examples",
      "persona_id": "pg-pg-010",
      "enriched_narrative": {
        "first_person": "I still remember getting sick from that canteen food in college \u2014 something about that experience rewired me completely. I can't just shrug off quality anymore, especially with what I eat or use daily. But living alone in Velachery on a middle income means every rupee genuinely counts, and I feel that pull constantly.\n\nBefore I buy anything significant, I'm running numbers in my head, cross-checking with what my friends actually use and swear by \u2014 not Instagram influencers, but people I trust who've made the same mistake of choosing cheap over good. My analytical side means I'll sit on a decision longer than most, comparing options obsessively, usually checking reviews on Flipkart or asking the group chat.\n\nIt's exhausting sometimes, honestly. I want the best version of something, but I can't always afford it. So I wait for the right moment, the right deal on Croma or DMart, without compromising too much on what actually matters.",
        "third_person": "Divya Krishnaswamy is a 28-year-old Chennai-based analytics professional navigating the familiar tension of wanting more than her single-income Velachery apartment budget comfortably allows. Her moderately analytical decision style means she does not act on impulse \u2014 she researches, compares, and deliberates before committing, particularly when money is involved. This careful approach stems partly from lived experience: a formative encounter with compromised food quality at her college canteen left a lasting impression, hardwiring a near-instinctive suspicion of anything that appears to cut corners.\n\nWhat makes Divya particularly interesting as a consumer is how her price sensitivity and quality orientation pull against each other simultaneously. She is not simply frugal, nor simply quality-driven \u2014 she is both, in constant negotiation. This tension rarely resolves cleanly, which is why peer validation becomes so structurally important to her. When her own judgment cannot confidently reconcile cost against quality, she offloads some of that cognitive burden to trusted friends and colleagues whose choices serve as proxies for reliability \u2014 validated through group chats and local recommendations rather than institutional endorsement. Peer endorsement effectively functions as informal quality assurance, reducing the perceived risk of a purchase she cannot afford to regret."
      },
      "cultural_references_added": [
        "Velachery (specific neighborhood, traces to life_story age 27)",
        "Flipkart (e-commerce platform, Chennai metro context, income_bracket supports)",
        "group chat (peer validation mechanism, age 28 professional cohort)",
        "Croma (electronics retailer, Chennai metro, middle-income shopping pattern)",
        "DMart (value retail chain, Chennai metro, price-sensitivity trace)"
      ],
      "contextual_examples_replaced": [
        {
          "original": "living alone in Chennai on a middle income",
          "replacement": "living alone in Velachery on a middle income",
          "attribute_source": "life_story.age_27, location.city"
