    {
      "enrichment_applied": true,
      "enrichment_provider": "sarvam",
      "enrichment_scope": "narrative_and_examples",
      "persona_id": "pg-pg-009",
      "enriched_narrative": {
        "first_person": "I've spent years building my ability to read a situation, weigh the evidence, and make the call myself. That instinct didn't come from nowhere \u2014 it came from watching a critical vendor handoff unravel spectacularly because I trusted the wrong people with something that mattered. Since then, self-reliance isn't just a preference; it's practically a reflex. But here's the uncomfortable truth I circle back to constantly: I can't scale myself. With a demanding role, a family of four in Mumbai, and decisions stacking up daily, I feel the pull to delegate, to trust someone else's judgment. And yet I hesitate \u2014 always wanting just one more data point, one more verified review before I let go. Price rarely stops me. What stops me is uncertainty. I'd rather pay more for something proven \u2014 whether it's a school with audited outcomes or an appliance with third-party testing \u2014 than save money on something I can't fully evaluate yet.",
        "third_person": "Rohan Mehta is a 36-year-old Mumbai-based professional whose decision-making is fundamentally shaped by a formative professional failure \u2014 a vendor data migration that unraveled days before a client presentation, leaving him to rebuild the pipeline overnight. This experience calcified into a default posture of self-reliance that now operates even when it creates bottlenecks. His analytical orientation \u2014 honed through rigorous postgraduate research on product quality and consumer trust \u2014 explains why information gaps are his primary source of decision friction. He does not move until sufficiently equipped, which means substantive, credible advertising genuinely influences him by closing those knowledge voids. Price rarely moves him; quality and perceived value dominate his lens across everything from D-Mart grocery choices to his children's school selection. The central paradox is that despite trusting himself above all else, Rohan is drawn to offloading decisions to others \u2014 a cognitive relief-seeking that his past betrayal makes feel unsafe. He oscillates between resisting delegation and craving it, never fully resolving the tension between control and release."
      },
      "cultural_references_added": [
