    {
      "enrichment_applied": true,
      "enrichment_provider": "sarvam",
      "enrichment_scope": "narrative_and_examples",
      "persona_id": "pg-pg-001",
      "enriched_narrative": {
        "first_person": "I still think about that laptop. Bought it cheap from a Bangalore street vendor near Commercial Street, convinced myself the specs were \"good enough\" \u2014 it died eight months later, two weeks before a crucial project deadline. That moment rewired something in me permanently.\n\nNow I live in this constant negotiation with myself. I research exhaustively before buying anything significant \u2014 specs, long-term reliability, what people I actually trust are using. My colleagues' opinions matter more to me than any tech review on 91mobiles or YouTube. If three people I respect own something and stand by it, that carries real weight.\n\nBut I'm also one person, single income, Bengaluru rent being what it is. I can't just buy the best version of everything. So I end up spending more time than I probably should analyzing whether a product genuinely earns its price \u2014 because cutting corners has already cost me more than saving money ever saved me.",
        "third_person": "Arjun Menon is a 29-year-old Bengaluru-based analyst navigating the familiar friction between aspiration and financial reality. Living alone in a single-occupancy flat on a middle income, his purchasing psychology was fundamentally shaped by a formative experience with a faulty budget laptop \u2014 an incident that embedded deep skepticism toward low-cost options and installed quality as his primary evaluative filter.\n\nDespite this quality orientation, Arjun is not impulsive. His analytically-driven decision style means he gathers information extensively before committing, often consulting trusted peers at coffee shops in Whitefield or browsing detailed product comparisons on tech forums rather than relying on brand messaging. This behavior stems directly from his trust anchor being himself \u2014 he cannot outsource confidence to advertising, so he compensates through peer validation and prolonged comparison.\n\nHis social circle functions as a validation mechanism; he observes what trusted colleagues have chosen before forming his own position. This explains his measured switching behavior \u2014 he resists change not from loyalty but from risk aversion, acutely aware of his budgetary ceiling while unwilling to compromise on durability."
      },
