    {
      "enrichment_applied": true,
      "enrichment_provider": "sarvam",
      "enrichment_scope": "narrative_and_examples",
      "persona_id": "pg-pg-003",
      "enriched_narrative": {
        "first_person": "I still think about that laptop I bought in my second year at Anna University. Saved money upfront, chose the cheaper option, and within eight months the hinge cracked, the battery swelled, and I'd spent more on repairs than the price difference ever justified. That experience rewired how I think about every purchase now.\n\nLiving alone in Velachery on a middle income means every rupee has a job. I run the numbers carefully\u2014I'm not impulsive. But I refuse to let budget pressure push me toward something that'll fail me. The tension is real and constant: I want the *right* thing, not just the affordable thing.\n\nI trust my own research over anyone's recommendation. If an ad from Flipkart or Amazon catches my attention, I'll investigate it thoroughly before it influences me. Shortcuts cost more. I learned that the hard way.",
        "third_person": "Karthik Rajan is a 27-year-old postgraduate professional living alone in Velachery, Chennai, navigating the early stages of a career that provides moderate but constrained financial flexibility. His consumer behavior is fundamentally shaped by a formative experience during his final semester at Anna University \u2014 a defective budget laptop purchase that cost him significantly more to repair than he had initially saved \u2014 which crystallized a core belief: cheap rarely means economical.\n\nThis history explains why Karthik operates with an analytical decision style. He researches methodically, cross-referencing advertising claims from platforms like Amazon and Flipkart against his own accumulated knowledge, since he trusts his own judgment above external sources. Advertising does reach him effectively, but primarily as a discovery mechanism rather than a persuasion tool \u2014 he filters promotional messaging through his own quality-value framework.\n\nHis central tension is structural: he deeply values quality but his middle income creates real budget pressure. This forces careful, deliberate trade-off analysis before every significant purchase. He rarely switches brands impulsively, preferring to weigh options thoroughly. Karthik essentially treats each purchase as a miniature risk assessment, seeking maximum quality per rupee spent."
      },
