    {
      "enrichment_applied": true,
      "enrichment_provider": "sarvam",
      "enrichment_scope": "narrative_and_examples",
      "persona_id": "pg-pg-017",
      "enriched_narrative": {
        "first_person": "I've spent thirty years watching colleagues cut corners and pay for it later. After what happened with that uncertified water purifier in Laxmi Nagar \u2014 the BIS certification incident that nearly cost us everything \u2014 I stopped gambling with quality. I simply don't.\n\nBut here's my daily reality: five people depend on this household running smoothly, and my salary has limits. So every significant purchase becomes a calculation I run in my head three, four times. Is this brand established? Does it carry proper BIS or ISI marks? Can I actually afford it without stretching dangerously?\n\nI'm not chasing luxury. I'm chasing verified, proven quality \u2014 the kind that Consumer Reports and established manufacturers stand behind. I'll wait an extra month, skip something else entirely, just to buy from Philips or ITC or Godrej. Cheap mistakes are the most expensive ones I know.",
        "third_person": "Raghav Pandey is a 55-year-old Delhi-based professional navigating the persistent tension between his aspiration for quality and the fiscal realities of supporting a joint household of five on a middle income. His decision-making, while moderately analytical, is deeply shaped by a formative experience with a water purifier lacking BIS certification that permanently recalibrated his understanding of trust and standards. This incident explains why Raghav does not simply seek cheap options \u2014 he seeks verified, credible ones bearing official marks like ISI or BIS, even when his budget resists.\n\nHis authority-trust orientation means he relies on established Indian and multinational brands \u2014 Philips, ITC, Godrej, Bajaj \u2014 and official certification bodies as proxies for quality assurance, reducing the cognitive burden of evaluation in a marketplace he regards with measured suspicion. Brand familiarity functions less as preference and more as risk mitigation for him.\n\nWhat drives his price sensitivity is not indifference to quality but rather the arithmetic of constrained resources. He weighs every purchase carefully because mistakes are costly. Loyalty to trusted brands emerges naturally from this logic \u2014 once a brand earns Raghav's confidence through demonstrated standards, switching carries risk he is unwilling to absorb."
      },
