    {
      "enrichment_applied": true,
      "enrichment_provider": "sarvam",
      "enrichment_scope": "narrative_and_examples",
      "persona_id": "pg-pg-012",
      "enriched_narrative": {
        "first_person": "I still remember the day my son got sick after that cooking oil \u2014 the one I'd bought because it was cheaper. The pediatrician's bills at Lilavati cost far more than I'd saved. That incident changed something in me permanently. I cannot compromise on what goes into my family's food or home, even when my budget screams otherwise.\n\nBut the tension is real and daily. I'm running spreadsheets in my head at every D-Mart aisle \u2014 is this worth it, what are my colleagues buying, have I checked BigBasket for a better deal? I ask around before I decide anything significant. My sister-in-law's recommendation carries more weight than any advertisement.\n\nI want the best for my three-person household. I just need to be absolutely certain I'm paying for genuine quality, not just a premium label.",
        "third_person": "Sheetal Joshi is a 33-year-old working professional based in Pune, navigating the dual pressures of early parenthood and middle-income financial constraints. Her postgraduate education equips her with the analytical tools to scrutinize purchases carefully, but her decision-making is rarely purely rational \u2014 it is emotionally anchored in a formative experience she calls the Adulterated Oil Incident, which permanently elevated food quality to a non-negotiable priority in her household.\n\nThis background explains the central tension in her behavior: she is highly price-sensitive yet deeply quality-driven, creating a persistent internal conflict before most purchasing decisions. She methodically compares options across D-Mart, BigBasket, and local Pune grocers, delaying commitment until confident about value per rupee spent.\n\nWhat makes Sheetal distinctive is her reliance on peer validation before forming conclusions. Her trust architecture centers on family consensus, with her sister-in-law functioning as her primary sounding board. She uses peer behavior as a proxy for safety \u2014 a logical shortcut given her real fear is not spending too much, but choosing wrong and bearing the health consequences her family cannot afford."
      },
      "cultural_references_added": [
